The paper deals with parallel algorithms for directed graphs, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The main problem addressed is that of digraph reachability, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and falls under the category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also presents an efficient Monte Carlo algorithm, which involves probabilistic analysis and falls under the category of Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM). The paper discusses the challenges of dealing with sparse high-diameter graphs, which is a topic in Network Science (cs.NE). Finally, the paper presents algorithms for topological sorting and directed ear decomposition, which are topics in Computational Complexity (cs.CC).
